<DOC><DOCNO> AP890315-0094 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-89 0734EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Korea     03-15 0314</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Korea,0324</SECOND><HEAD>Radical Students Clash With Riot Police In Three Cities</HEAD><BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Hundreds of radical students foughtriot police with clubs, firebombs and rocks in three cities todayand announced a nationwide campaign to defeat President Roh Tae-wooin an upcoming referendum.   The student councils of 38 colleges and universities in Seoulsaid they would launch anti-government protests to overthrow Roh'sgovernment in alliance with dissident political groups.   About 700 students, shouting ``Down with Roh Tae-woo!'', battledriot police who responded with tear gas for an hour outside the maingate of Seoul's Sejong University. No arrests or injuries werereported.   Fighting also broke out at Dankuk University in southern Seoulwhere about 500 students, demanding Roh's resignation and a halt tojoint U.S.-South Korea military exercises now being held, tried tomarch into the streets.   Police fired tear gas to disperse the protesters after a two-hourbattle.   In the central city of Taejon, about 1,000 students, hurlingfirebombs and rocks, battled riot police who retaliated with teargas, news reports said. The protesters shouted slogans against Rohand his government.   In the southern city of Kwangju, the South Korean news agencyYonhap reported, about 5,000 students held an anti-Roh rally andvowed to defeat the president in the referendum, which is expectedto be held next month.   Roh said in a 1987 campaign pledge that he would seek a midtermappraisal of his performance after the Seoul Olympics, which endedlast October. Under pressure from the opposition, he said last weekthat he would fulfill the pledge by holding a referendum.   Roh has said that in the referendum people would be simply askedto assess the progress of democratic reforms he has introduced sincehis inauguration 13 months ago.   May people think the reforms, which have included greater pressfreedom, are insufficient.</TEXT></DOC>